# Hardware Components

The prototype of the **Modular Wireless Headphone System** is developed using reusable and commercially available electronic components. The primary objective is 
to transform a legacy Bluetooth headphone into a modular wireless audio platform while improving repairability, battery life, and future upgrade capability.

### Components Used

1. Panasonic RP-BTD5 Bluetooth Motherboard
* Original Bluetooth audio control PCB
* Bluetooth communication module
* Integrated charging and audio control circuitry
* Reused as the primary wireless controller

2. Sennheiser HD 202 Wired Headphones
* High-quality dynamic headphone drivers
* Used as the dedicated audio output device
* The frequency response of the HD 202 II is between 18 Hz to 18 KHz.
* The Sennheiser HD 202 headphones feature large 40 mm dynamic drivers equipped with neodymium magnets and ultra-lightweight diaphragms ensuring superior Audio 
  quality in all terms.
* Original AUX cable permanently connected to the Bluetooth motherboard

3. 1500 mAh Lithium-Ion Battery
* Replaces the original 650 mAh battery
* Provides significantly longer playback time
* Rechargeable single-cell battery

4. USB Type-C Charging Module (Optional) as traditionally this module equipped with Micro-USB charging port
* Replaces the original Micro-USB charging interface
* Improves connector durability and ease of use
* Provides compatibility with modern USB Type-C charging cables

5. 100 kΩ Resistor
* Used for signal conditioning where required
* Helps stabilize the audio signal and minimize unwanted fluctuations during operation
* Protects sensitive audio circuitry under specific operating conditions

6. Audio Amplifier Module (CT14 Series – Optional)
* Can be integrated if additional audio amplification is required
* Improves output drive capability for higher-impedance headphones
* Optional depending on the final audio output level

7. Connecting Wires and Solder Joints
* Used to establish permanent electrical connections between hardware components
* Ensures reliable signal transmission and mechanical stability

### Design Philosophy

Instead of manufacturing a completely new wireless headphone, this project focuses on extending the useful life of existing electronic hardware through 
modular integration. The Bluetooth motherboard, battery, charging interface, and audio output are designed as replaceable components, allowing future 
maintenance, upgrades, and hardware experimentation without replacing the entire system. This modular approach supports sustainable electronics, reduces 
electronic waste, and encourages repair-friendly product design.
